04643nam a22006375i 9780271033136DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212005pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710331367 a10.1515/97802710331362doi  a(DE-B1597)584010  a(OCoLC)1262307430  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a261.8/082/09812221 aDrogus, Carol Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aActivist Faith :bGrassroots Women in Democratic Brazil and Chile /cCarol Ann Drogus, Hannah Stewart-Gambino. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tLIST OF ACRONYMS -- t1 Activism and Its Aftermath -- t2 Understanding Invisibility: Perspectives on Social Movement Decline -- t3 Resurrecting Civil Society: Christian Base Communities Under Military Rule -- t4 Earthquake Versus Erosion: Church Retreat and Social Movement Decline -- t5 Keeping the Faith: Empowerment and Activism in a New Era -- t6 Catholics and Pentecostals: Possibilities for Alliance -- t7 Activist Women and Women's Activists: Possibilities for Networking with Feminist Groups -- t8 Legacies of Activism: Personal Empowerment, Movement Survival -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a";An extensive and powerful literature on religion, society, and politics in Latin America in recent years has begun with the assumption that most of the movements that surged in the struggle against military rule are dead, that most of the activists are scattered and burned out, and that the promise of civil society as a source of new values and a new kind of citizenship and political life was illusory. Many have assumed that the religiously inspired activism of that period left little lasting impact, but hardly anyone has actually looked at the activists themselves to see what remains, how they cope in a different, more open environment, and how they see and act on the present and future. Activist Faith addresses these issues with a wealth of empirical detail from two key cases and with a richly interdisciplinary argument that draws on theorizing about social movements. The authors strive to understand what sustains activism and movements in radically different circumstances from those in which they arose. Their analysis is enriched by systematic attention to the impact of gender and gender-related issues on activism and movements. In the process, they shed much needed light on the fate of the activists and social movements that rose to prominence throughout Latin America during the 1980s.This beautifully written book is a major achievement that gives us analytical tools for studying how movements and activists survive in the doldrums and when a cycle of protest peaks and societies move on.";-Daniel H. Levine, University of Michigan  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh1 aStewart-Gambino, Hannah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271033136zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271033136423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271033136.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  